On 5/13/16 1:58 PM, Bob Doe wrote:
> Great.  This is exactly what I am looking for.
> I have a couple more questions for you.
> If I have an association assoc = <|"a" -> 1, "b" -> 2, "c" -> 3|>, how would I add another key-value pair, like "d" -> 4, to the existing association?
The function AssociateTo can add a key-value pair to an association in 
place. For example, you could do AssociateTo[assoc, {"d" -> 4, "e" -> 
5}], and assoc would now be <|"a" -> 1, "b" -> 2, "c" -> 3, "d" -> 4, 
"e" -> 5|>.
> Also I noticed if I try to get the value assoc["z"], it returns Missing["KeyAbsent"]. Is there any way I could instead get the value 0 if the key doesn't exist?
There is another function called Lookup which returns the value 
associated with a key if it exists, and takes an optional third 
parameter to define a default return value.
Lookup[assoc, "z", 0] should do what you're looking for.
